<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
This species was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Han, YF" journalOrPublisher="Acta Entomologica Sinica" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="337 - 340" refId="B5" refString="Han, YF, Cui, YQ, Hu, XG, Cui, WQ, 1991. Two new species of Phlaeothripids from Hengduan Mountains, China (Thysanoptera: Phlaeothripidae). Acta Entomologica Sinica 34 (3): 337 - 340" title="Two new species of Phlaeothripids from Hengduan Mountains, China (Thysanoptera: Phlaeothripidae)." volume="34" year="1991">Han et al. (1991)</bibRefCitation>
from Sichuan Province and Tibet based on two females. In the present study, we checked the two type specimens. They were squashed (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–5" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 5. Apterygothrips brunneicornus. Holotype female (1 - 4) 1 adult 2 head, pronotum and fore legs 3 tergites IX-X 4 antenna; paratype female (5) 5 paratype female: head, pronotum and fore legs. Scale bars: 100 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1112.85902.figures1-5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/713603" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">1</figureCitation>
), but fortunately the major characters could be seen. 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Apterygothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Apterygothrips brunneicornus" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brunneicornus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Apterygothrips brunneicornus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. flavescens" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="flavescens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A. flavescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Dang &amp; Qiao sp. nov. in having major setae pointed (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–5" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 5. Apterygothrips brunneicornus. Holotype female (1 - 4) 1 adult 2 head, pronotum and fore legs 3 tergites IX-X 4 antenna; paratype female (5) 5 paratype female: head, pronotum and fore legs. Scale bars: 100 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1112.85902.figures1-5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/713603" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–5" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 5. Apterygothrips brunneicornus. Holotype female (1 - 4) 1 adult 2 head, pronotum and fore legs 3 tergites IX-X 4 antenna; paratype female (5) 5 paratype female: head, pronotum and fore legs. Scale bars: 100 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1112.85902.figures1-5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/713603" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3</figureCitation>
), and it comes from the same location: Tibet. It can be distinguished by having body uniformly brown (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–5" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 5. Apterygothrips brunneicornus. Holotype female (1 - 4) 1 adult 2 head, pronotum and fore legs 3 tergites IX-X 4 antenna; paratype female (5) 5 paratype female: head, pronotum and fore legs. Scale bars: 100 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1112.85902.figures1-5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/713603" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">1</figureCitation>
), antenna brown with segment III paler at base (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–5" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 5. Apterygothrips brunneicornus. Holotype female (1 - 4) 1 adult 2 head, pronotum and fore legs 3 tergites IX-X 4 antenna; paratype female (5) 5 paratype female: head, pronotum and fore legs. Scale bars: 100 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1112.85902.figures1-5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/713603" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–5" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 5. Apterygothrips brunneicornus. Holotype female (1 - 4) 1 adult 2 head, pronotum and fore legs 3 tergites IX-X 4 antenna; paratype female (5) 5 paratype female: head, pronotum and fore legs. Scale bars: 100 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1112.85902.figures1-5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/713603" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">4</figureCitation>
), antennal segment IV with 1+2 sense cones, fore tarsal tooth present (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–5" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 5. Apterygothrips brunneicornus. Holotype female (1 - 4) 1 adult 2 head, pronotum and fore legs 3 tergites IX-X 4 antenna; paratype female (5) 5 paratype female: head, pronotum and fore legs. Scale bars: 100 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1112.85902.figures1-5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/713603" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">5</figureCitation>
), pronotum with five pairs of well-developed setae (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–5" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 5. Apterygothrips brunneicornus. Holotype female (1 - 4) 1 adult 2 head, pronotum and fore legs 3 tergites IX-X 4 antenna; paratype female (5) 5 paratype female: head, pronotum and fore legs. Scale bars: 100 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1112.85902.figures1-5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/713603" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">2</figureCitation>
) and by its pelta shape (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 14–21" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 14 - 21. Apterygothrips spp. A. flavescens Dang &amp; Qiao sp. nov. (14 - 20) 14 adult, female 15 adult, male 16 head, pronotum and fore legs 17 tergites IX-X, female 18 tergites IX-X, male 19 tergites V-VI 20 pelta; A. brunneicornus (21): 21 pelta. Scale bars: 100 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1112.85902.figures14-21" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/713605" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">21</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
